<div id=3D"how-it-works">
<h3>How the Derivative Calculator Works</h3>
<p>For those with a technical background, the following section explains ho=
w the Derivative Calculator works.</p><p>First, a <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=
=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parser">parser</a> anal=
yzes the mathematical function. It transforms it into a form that is better=
 understandable by a computer, namely a tree (see figure below). In doing t=
his, the Derivative Calculator has to respect the <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=
=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_operations">or=
der of operations</a>. A specialty in mathematical expressions is that the =
multiplication sign can be left out sometimes, for example we write <code>5=
x</code> instead of <code>5*x</code>. The Derivative Calculator has to dete=
ct these cases and insert the multiplication sign.</p><p>The parser is impl=
emented in <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/JavaScript">JavaScript</a>, based on the <a rel=3D"nofollow" c=
lass=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shunting-yard_algor=
ithm">Shunting-yard algorithm</a>, and can run directly in the browser. Thi=
s allows for quick feedback while typing by transforming the tree into <a r=
el=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La=
TeX">LaTeX</a> code. <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external" href=3D"https:/=
/www.mathjax.org/">MathJax</a> takes care of displaying it in the browser.<=
/p><p>When the "<em>Go!</em>" button is clicked, the Derivative Calculator =
sends the mathematical function and the settings (differentiation variable =
and order) to the server, where it is analyzed again. This time, the functi=
on gets transformed into a form that can be understood by the <a rel=3D"nof=
ollow" class=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_al=
gebra_system">computer algebra system</a> <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"exte=
rnal" href=3D"http://maxima.sourceforge.net/">Maxima</a>.</p><p><img src=3D=
"https://www.derivative-calculator.net/layout/xhow-it-works.png,q1715177718=
.pagespeed.ic.Xand2xCNWa.webp" width=3D"800" height=3D"259" loading=3D"lazy=
" alt=3D"How the Derivative Calculator works"></p><p>Maxima takes care of a=
ctually computing the derivative of the mathematical function. Like any com=
puter algebra system, it applies a number of rules to simplify the function=
 and calculate the derivatives according to the commonly known <a rel=3D"no=
follow" class=3D"external" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differenti=
ation_rules">differentiation rules</a>. Maxima's output is transformed to L=
aTeX again and is then presented to the user.</p><p>Displaying the steps of=
 calculation is a bit more involved, because the Derivative Calculator can'=
t completely depend on Maxima for this task. Instead, the derivatives have =
to be calculated manually step by step. The rules of differentiation (produ=
ct rule, quotient rule, chain rule, =E2=80=A6) have been implemented in Jav=
aScript code. There is also a table of derivative functions for the trigono=
metric functions and the square root, logarithm and exponential function. I=
n each calculation step, one differentiation operation is carried out or re=
written. For example, constant factors are pulled out of differentiation op=
erations and sums are split up (sum rule). This, and general simplification=
s, is done by Maxima. For each calculated derivative, the LaTeX representat=
ions of the resulting mathematical expressions are tagged in the HTML code =
so that highlighting is possible.</p><p>The "Check&nbsp;answer" feature has=
 to solve the difficult task of determining whether two mathematical expres=
sions are equivalent. Their difference is computed and simplified as far as=
 possible using Maxima. For example, this involves writing trigonometric/hy=
perbolic functions in their exponential forms. If it can be shown that the =
difference simplifies to zero, the task is solved. Otherwise, a probabilist=
ic algorithm is applied that evaluates and compares both functions at rando=
mly chosen places.</p><p>The interactive function graphs are computed in th=
e browser and displayed within a <a class=3D"external" rel=3D"nofollow" hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canvas_element">canvas element (HTML5)</=
a>. For each function to be graphed, the calculator creates a JavaScript fu=
nction, which is then evaluated in small steps in order to draw the graph. =
While graphing, singularities (e.g. poles) are detected and treated special=
ly. The gesture control is implemented using <a class=3D"external" rel=3D"n=
ofollow" href=3D"https://hammerjs.github.io/">Hammer.js</a>.</p><p>If you h=
ave any questions or ideas for improvements to the Derivative Calculator, d=
on't hesitate to <a rel=3D"nofollow" href=3D"mailto:d.scherfgen@googlemail.=
com">write me an e-mail</a>.</p>
